e 0\) ) leads to chiral charge energy pumping between the opposite Chirality nodes. This results in chiral charge and energy imbalance between the Weyl nodes, which manifests in magneto-transport phenomena. Consider a Weyl semimetal with one pair of Weyl points of opposite Chirality (which act as Berry curvature monopoles), which are separated in the momentum space by \(\delta 	extbf{K}\) and in energy space by \(\Delta\) . This \(\Delta\) is known as chiral chemical potential and is odd under ( \(\mathcal{P}\) ) operation. The nonconservation of chiral charge in the presence of electric field ( \(	extbf{E} \cdot 	extbf{B} 
e 0\) ) is known as electrical Chiral Anomaly . Schematic of the CCP ( \(\delta \mu\) ) imbalance in Weyl semimetal Such a system breaks both the Time reversal symmetry ( \(\mathcal{T}\) ) and \(\mathcal{P}\) symmetry. This system possesses a dynamic magnetoelectric coupling \(	heta(	extbf{x},t) 	extbf{E} \cdot 	extbf{B}\) , where \(	heta(	extbf{x},t) = (\delta 	extbf{K} \cdot 	extbf{x} - \Delta T)\) . Since \(\delta 	extbf{K}\) and \(\Delta\) are respectively odd under Time reversal symmetry and inversion symmetry, this magnetoelectric coupling leads to the anomalous charge current. \( \(j =  rac{e^2}{h} \delta 	extbf{K} 	imes 	extbf{E} +  rac{e^2}{h^2} \Delta B\) \) In the absence of \(\mathcal{T}\) symmetry, the spatial gradient \(	heta(	extbf{x},t)\) governs the anomalous charge Hall current. In contrast, the time derivative of \(	heta(	extbf{x},t)\) induces a current along the direction of the applied MF for the inversion-asymmetric Weyl semimetal , which is known as chiral magnetic current. Time dependent MF can create a response known as Dynamic chiral magnetic effect .

